							<Data><![CDATA[About FAT TextThe texts are a vital part in a learning production and there are many demands to fulfill - translations, global texts, template texts, cloned texts etc. This explains how the fields in FAT Text are set up in the FAT.An important definitionAll texts that are displayed in a production belongs to each title. There are no true “global” texts after creation of a new title. The new title will get its own instances of the global texts. Primary keyEach text field has a unique primary key, given on creation or import. However,  depending on the origin of the text (it can be cloned or translated for example) this is not key when the text is exported to a JSON-file.TextText is the text entered, it can be with html-tags or without. Text will be exported  UTF-8-encoded.Enter time and Exit timeTime - Only used for subtitle text for a video or audio file.Source reference - Generic FAT itemsThe source reference is used in different ways depending on source item type. For the generic cmt items - title, package, chapter, page and page-item - the reference is pointing to the specifc text field inside this item, i.e “FAT Page item::Text 4 id”, “FAT Content array @ Page item::Text 3 id” or “FAT Chapter::Title txt id”. These references are not used in the code, it’s only for development and test. Source reference - when source item type = mediaFor a media file, texts are used for subtitles (closed captions) and the reference will be either “Subtitle FFSub” (for Funkis video) or “Subtitle VTT” (for native video). This is decided by media field playAsNativeVideo.Source reference - when source item type = globalA global text is a text that can occure in different places of the production. It can be text in dialog boxes or texts connected to a specific Block. Each global text belongs to the Title but its origin may come from a block template or a code base.Global text - the text belongs to the Title. Block text - the text belongs to a specific Block and the text will be the same each time the block is being used. I.e “Read more...” “Your score” etc. Source reference - when source item type = global codebaseA global codebase text is a text that can occure in different places of the production and belong to a specific codebase (template project). These texts can either be Global text codebase or Block template text.Global text codebase will be cloned into a global - Global text for each Title. This text exist in both a primary (en-global) and a secondary (sv-se) language.Block template text - this text belongs to the template and is being cloned as a global - Block text each time the template is being used in a Block in a Title. This text exist in both a primary (en-global) and a secondary (sv-se) language.Source reference - when source item type = attributeFAT AttributeValue::Text id - it is possible to have a text field connected to an attribute value. The parent for the text field is the FAT AttributeValue.THE STATUS FIELDStatus can beHidden - only original localisations code. Set in Media subtitle view. Text with status "Hidden" is not exported. Not translated - Text with a different localisation code than original. Same text as original localisationNot reviewed - Text with a different localisation code than original. Translated but not reviewed in FAT.In progress - Text with a different localisation code than original. Set by reviewer in FAT. Approved - Text with a different localisation code than original. Set by reviewer in FAT.]]></Data>
